beer_description:
Styles ? a consumer?s best friend, a brewer?s set of shackles! Though we have settled for Golden Ale on the label, Gabriel simply doesn?t quite fit into any existing style. It?s always a little more X or a little less Y. Perhaps it needs some Z? Whatever Gabriel isn?t doesn?t matter. Here?s what it is.
Gabriel is straw to pale golden colour, with a sweet biscuit malt base, and of course a good dosing of New Zealand?s finest aromatic hops, giving enticing aroma and flavour notes of gooseberry, citrus and a hint of peach. Almost a Golden Ale, Not quite a New World Pilsner, it?s Gabriel and we?re pretty sure you will like it.

IPA is the worlds most loved craft beer style so of course we were going to make one ? and we made sure it was a good one! Although not of typical IPA alcohol strength, Roulette offers the same hop punch of its stronger brothers but is a little more sessionable.
Pouring a dark straw hue, Roulette offers a fresh aroma and flavour with suggestions of passionfruit and orange/grapefruit from the NZ Riwaka and NZ Chinook, hops combining with light caramel from the blend of malts.

History records Honey Wine (Mead) as the Honeymoon drink, said to aid your prowess as a lover. True to tradition 1st Night Honey Wine is lovingly made by slow fermentation of specially selected pure honey from New Zealands beautiful East Coast region. A delightful drink in it?s own right 1st Night has robust Manuka flavours and great body with a smooth, balanced finish. Fuel love?s flame.
The Nose has distinctive full yet delicate Honey and Citrus Aromas. In the mouth there is a smooth rounded body to the wine with intense Unique Manuka flavours dominating the palate upfront, leading to a clean balanced finish where the acidity compliments the sweet honey aftertaste.

Bottled. An amber mead with gold chunks floating around - looking expensive. The aroma has intensive notes of honey, rose hips, and spices. The flavor is sweet with strong notes honey and alcohol, as well as medium rose hips and spices, leading to a dry finish. The alcohol burns the tongue. So this is what gold tastes like.

All Kingston Ciders reflect our commitment and passion for producing quality traditional ciders harvested with exceptional New Zealand fruit. All our ciders have been made with absolute minimal intervention to allow the intense vibrant fruit flavours to shine through.

Brouwerij Contreras, formerly called Latte Brewery is a Belgian family brewery founded in 1818 by Valere Latte and located in the East Flemish town Gavere. The company was owned by the family when Rene Contreras Contreras it bought up in 1898. He sold the company in 1920 to his nephew Marcel Contreras. His son Willy Contreras later took over the helm. The brewery is now run by the couple Frederik De Vrieze and Anne Contreras (daughter of Willy Contreras).
Our finest India Pale Ale, for true IPA connoisseurs

Cornish Stout is brewed with roasted barley, wheat and crystal rye for an intensely roasted character. Apollo hops provide a resinous aniseed backbone and slow fermentation gives the beer a chocolate sweetness.

Beware of beer. There, we warned you. The frothy head, and pungent, piney dry hopped scent (from Cascade and Amarillo hops) should alert you to the brew?s imminent attack on your senses. Next, Cascade, Perle and Willamette hops will batter your palette with bitter ferocity. Finally, Pale, Crystal (30 and 75) and wheat malts converge in a cloudy, think body and give you a smooth kiss of sweet death - and leave you howling for more!

Red Racer Pumpkin Ale is an amber ale with added spices and flavour to make for a rich and full seasonal ale fit for any holiday feast.

Malts ? Munich, Pale, Cara Vienne, Cara Munich

Hops ? German Perle

Colour/Clarity: Orange, Bright

Available In: Draught, Bottles (650 ml)

beer_name: Bat out of Hell Oak Aged Version
Monk's Caf? Cuvee de Monk's Gueuze
Flandre-Kent Les Fr?res De La Bi?re / Thiriez XXtra

beer_description: A strong IPA made with 100% Maris Otter low colour malt and  a combination of two New Zealand hops to give a full flavoured pale beer. Hop flavours predominate with summer fruits, earthy and grassy flavours all present. The finish is long-lasting and bitter leaving an overall impression of crispness alongside warming alcohol.

With its unique citrus character, smooth drinkability, and distinctive hop character, Drifter Pale Ale is truly an original. Brewed with generous amounts of Summit hops, a variety known for their intense citrus flavors and aromas, Drifter has a taste unique to the Pale Ale category. 
2006 GABF Silver Medal Winner
Roast barley flavour with Port overtones.

This bracingly strong drop, a local favourite, was the first commercial Helle Bock born in NZ. Its a German style lager, characterised by high strength, sweet malt flavours and full body, with the Nelson Sauvin hops putting subtle gooseberry tones against the grains.
Our lightest beer, Cow Town is a uniquely refreshing wheat ale made from Kansas grown wheat and Munich malts, topped with Hallertauer and Willamette hops.

Unmistakably malty, Possum Trot draws its inspiration from the classic brown ales of England. This unique style, given Kansas City's original nickname, combines a variety of barley to produce a toasty, nutty malt flavor with a slight hop bitterness in the finish for balance. Gold Medal Winner at the 1997 Great American Beer Festival. Bronze Medal Winner at the 1998 International World Beer Cup.

A dry Irish-style stout, Muddy Mo? is full-bodied with a wonderful aroma. The chocolate malt topped with Cluster hops combines remarkable creaminess, smooth drinkability and the hearty, robust flavor of a classic Irish stout. Often called the best stout this side of Dublin.
Our top selling, award winning, best bitter. A light amber colour. TEA is refreshing, hoppy and well balanced. Surely the best drink of the day!

O'Malley's SunRye?s Ale is the perfect beer drinker?s summer brew. Not a watered down seasonal substitute, SunRye?s offers a complex combination of the golden malts and gives the smoothest finish yet. It?s about time summer had a real beer.

Brewed in celebration of the U-District?s most misunderstood denizen, the ?Ave Rat.? Stylistically, it?s a strong pre-Prohibition West Coast adjunct lager, brewed with Pilsner malt, flaked maize, and Styrian Goldings, which blend together into a rich, golden beer that is smooth, refreshing, and only a little bit edgy.
This American malt liquor was hand crafted with fine German hops, 25% Illinois corn, and a sense of purpose.
Malt Liquor

Brewed at the Weltenburger Monastery, which was founded in 45 AD, with the brewery established in 1050. This is the world's oldest dark beer. A true experience of flavour. Full bodied, with fine malt aromas. Slightly bitter with some sweetness, creamy and with the warm colours of amber, intensive flavour and fragrance. Brewed in the traditional monastic manner, it's regarded as one of the great beers.

A very fruity, amber ale produced each year for the festive season. It?s brewed with a triple-hop mix of Challenger, Northern Brewer and Goldings which gives it an almost spicy flavour. ??It was originally a one-off brew that was launched in 2005 at the beer festival at the Bell Inn, Nottingham.

Our dark wheat beer is impressive with its creamy white foam. A fruity-fresh sweetness and hints of mature bananas harmonise with delicious flavours of roasted malt, sparkling and full-bodied with a light caramel taste on the first sip. An excellent accompaniment from hearty meals and game to chocolate and nut desserts. Brewed according to our centuries-old brewing tradition on the Weihenstephan hill.

Geary?s new Winter Ale is a dark rye ale. Well balanced and more aggressive, both in alcohol and hop character, without being overpowering. Malt flavors are toasty and fruity, resulting in a tasty blend with firm body balanced by English hops.
This bright garnet holiday treat is made from raspberries from the northwest. Refreshing, ripe raspberry flavor, tart and complex.
This 3.8% ale is a light chestnut ale with a fruity nose. The spicy notes of this festive ale harmonise to leave a delightful refreshing hoppy finish.

The name of this beer has been the topic of many great (and sometimes unusual and awkward) conversations, and has even garnered the blessing of a priest as a Brew Fest. It is brewed with tons of delicious secret malts and loads upon loads of glorious hops, and finally dry hopped with copious amounts of Cascade Hops.
Kettle Soured Raspberry Blonde Ale. Tart & Snappy, Crisp & Fruity
An all organic brown on nitrogen.

Robust & malty Imperial stout, brewed with English hops, chocolate malt, Oregon sweet cherries, and Love! Pours a deep brown with a creamy light beige head. Heavy notes of chocolate, tart cherries, and coffee roast.

Traditionally made strong & highly hopped so it would keep on its long journey, from England to India during British rule. This one is a BIG & BAD,misbehaving, India Pale Ale, wonderfully bitter beer with a spicy aroma, some fruity characteristics and a lingering hop finish. A great aperitif! (Something Normal All ?Fouled? Up)
